.TH FFPDF 1 "July 2026" "ffpdf 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ffpdf \- extract and fill PDF form fields
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ffpdf
.B fdf-extract
.I pdf
.br
.B ffpdf
.B xfdf-extract
.I pdf
.br
.B ffpdf
.B fields
.I pdf
.br
.B ffpdf
.B fill
.RB [ \-f | \-\-flatten ]
.RB [ \-o
.IR file ]
.RB [ \-\- ]
.I fdf pdf
.br
.B ffpdf
.B xref
.I pdf
.br
.B ffpdf
.RB { help | version }
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ffpdf
is a small, fast command-line tool for reading and filling PDF
.B AcroForm
form fields. It is written in C and depends only on
.BR zlib :
no Java, no external PDF toolkit, and no headless browser.
.PP
The typical loop is
.BR discover " \(-> " edit " \(-> " fill :
list a form's fields with
.BR "ffpdf fdf-extract" ,
edit the resulting FDF to set the values you want, then produce a filled PDF
with
.BR "ffpdf fill" .
.PP
Every command writes its result to
.BR "standard output" ;
progress messages and warnings go to
.B standard error
so they never corrupt the output stream. Fills are written as PDF
.I incremental updates:
the original bytes are preserved verbatim and the changes are appended,
so nothing existing is rewritten.
.SH COMMANDS
Exactly one command must be given.
.TP
.BI fdf-extract " pdf"
Extract every fillable (terminal) form field of
.I pdf
and print them as an
.B FDF
document on standard output. Each field appears as a
.RB \(dq "/T (name) /V (value)" \(dq
entry; the
.B /T
is the fully\-qualified field name you fill by.
.TP
.BI xfdf-extract " pdf"
As
.BR fdf-extract ,
but emit the field list as an
.B XFDF
(XML) document instead.
.TP
.BI fields " pdf"
List every fillable field as
.B JSON
on standard output: each field's fully-qualified name, type
.RB ( text ,
.BR button ,
.BR choice ,
.BR signature ),
and current value, plus a choice field's options and combo/multi-select flags
and a checkbox's on-state name. This is the machine-readable companion to
.BR fdf-extract ,
intended for scripts and AI agents that need to know what a form accepts
before filling it.
.TP
.BI fill " \fR[\fP\-f\fR|\fP\-\-flatten\fR] [\fP\-o \fIfile\fR] [\fP\-\-\fR]\fP fdf pdf"
Fill
.I pdf
using the values in
.IR fdf ,
writing the resulting PDF to standard output. Note the argument order:
the
.B FDF
comes first, then the
.BR PDF .
.I fdf
may be
.B \-
to read the FDF from standard input.
The tool selects each field's correct type behaviour (checkbox on\-state,
choice selection index, text appearance) and, for forms carrying an XFA data
packet, keeps that packet in sync so viewers that render XFA show the values.
As a safety net,
.B fill
refuses to write PDF bytes to a terminal; redirect the output or use
.BR \-o .
.IP
With
.B \-\-flatten
(or
.BR \-f ),
the result is additionally
.I flattened:
the filled values are baked into the page content and the interactive form
(widget annotations, the AcroForm, and any XFA packet) is removed, producing a
non\-editable PDF. Useful for archival or distribution when the values should no
longer be changed.
.IP
With
.BI \-o " file"
(or
.BR \-\-output ),
the PDF is written to
.I file
instead of standard output,
.IR atomically :
the output is assembled as
.IB file .tmp
and renamed into place only on success, so a failed or interrupted fill never
leaves a partial
.IR file .
.RB \(dq "\-o \-" \(dq
means standard output explicitly.
.IP
.B \-\-
ends option parsing, for file names that begin with
.RB \(dq \- \(dq.
The extraction and
.B xref
commands accept it too.
.TP
.BI xref " pdf"
Parse the cross\-reference table of
.I pdf
and dump it as JSON. This is a debugging and inspection aid, not part of the
fill workflow.
.TP
.B help
Print a usage summary to standard output and exit successfully.
Also accepted as
.B \-h
or
.BR \-\-help .
.TP
.B version
Print version and license information and exit successfully.
Also accepted as
.B \-v
or
.BR \-\-version .
.SH "FIELD TYPES"
All four AcroForm field types are handled:
.BR text ,
.B button
(checkbox / radio; values such as
.BR Yes ,
.BR On ,
or
.B 1
map to the widget's real on\-state),
.B choice
(combo box and list box, single or multi\-select), and
.B signature
(left untouched; a signature is not a fillable value). Non\-ASCII text
values are written as UTF\-16.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B FFPDF_VERBOSE
When set to
.BR 1 ,
filled values are included in the progress log on standard error. They are
redacted by default because form values may be sensitive (PHI/PII).
.TP
.B PDF_MAX_DECOMPRESSED
Maximum size of any single decompressed stream (default 256 MB). A stream that
would exceed this is treated as corrupt and skipped.
.TP
.B PDF_MAX_TOTAL_DECOMPRESSED
Maximum total decompressed bytes over one run (default 1 GB).
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
An error occurred: invalid usage, a file that could not be opened, or a PDF
whose cross\-reference table could not be parsed.
.SH EXAMPLES
List the fields of a form:
.PP
.RS
.EX
ffpdf fdf-extract form.pdf
.EE
.RE
.PP
Fill a form and save the result:
.PP
.RS
.EX
ffpdf fill answers.fdf form.pdf > filled.pdf
.EE
.RE
.PP
Fill and flatten to a non-editable PDF, written atomically with \-o:
.PP
.RS
.EX
ffpdf fill \-\-flatten \-o final.pdf answers.fdf form.pdf
.EE
.RE
.PP
Bulk fill (mail merge): pipe a templated FDF straight in (no temp file):
.PP
.RS
.EX
envsubst < template.fdf | ffpdf fill \-o out.pdf \- form.pdf
.EE
.RE
.PP
A minimal
.I answers.fdf
setting two fields:
.PP
.RS
.EX
%FDF\-1.2
1 0 obj
<< /FDF << /Fields [
  << /T (applicant_name) /V (Ada Lovelace) >>
  << /T (agree) /V (Yes) >>
] >> >>
endobj
trailer
<< /Root 1 0 R >>
%%EOF
.EE
.RE
.SH LIMITATIONS
Only the empty user password is supported for encrypted PDFs; files that
require a real password are not opened (by design; this is not a password
cracker).
.PP
Field extraction reads the AcroForm field tree. Purely
.I dynamic XFA
forms (for example many USCIS forms) keep their fields only in the XFA
template, not the AcroForm tree; for those,
.B fdf-extract
and
.B xfdf-extract
find nothing to extract.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
The
.B README.md
shipped with the source for a fuller guide, and ISO 32000\-1 (PDF) plus the
Adobe FDF/XFDF specifications for the underlying formats.
